<p>Warren Buffett is one of the wealthiest people in the world. He built his fortune through disciplined investing, but the real engine of his success is something far simpler: he reads. Every day, Buffett spends five to six hours reading newspapers, financial reports, industry publications, and books. When asked about the secret to his success, he pointed to a stack of papers and said, "Read 500 pages like this every day. That is how knowledge works. It builds up, like compound interest."</p>

<h2>The Reading Routine That Built a Fortune</h2>
<p>Buffett's reading habit is not casual. It is systematic and relentless. He estimates that he spends about 80 percent of his working day reading and thinking. This has been his routine for decades. When he first started his investment partnership in the 1950s, he would read annual reports of every publicly traded company in the United States. He read Moody's Manuals, thousands of pages of dense financial data, cover to cover. He was not looking for shortcuts or tips. He was building a mental database of business knowledge that would serve him for the rest of his life.</p>
<p>The key insight is that Buffett was not reading for entertainment. He was reading for knowledge accumulation. Every fact he learned, every industry he studied, every company he analyzed added to his mental library. Over decades, this library became so comprehensive that he could make investment decisions faster and more accurately than almost anyone else. He was not smarter than other investors. He simply had more relevant knowledge, acquired through more consistent reading, over a longer period of time.</p>

<h2>Compound Interest Applied to Knowledge</h2>
<p>Buffett often talks about compound interest as the most powerful force in investing. But he applies the same principle to knowledge. Every book you read, every article you study, every fact you learn adds to your knowledge base, and that knowledge compounds over time. The more you know, the easier it is to learn new things because you can connect new information to existing knowledge. This is exactly how the brain works: new information is encoded more effectively when it can be linked to existing neural networks.</p>
<p>This is also why spaced repetition is so effective. Each review of a piece of information strengthens the neural connections that encode it, and each connection makes it easier to connect future related information. The FSRS algorithm optimizes this process by scheduling reviews at the moment when the connection is weakest, maximizing the strengthening effect of each review. Over months and years, the cumulative effect of thousands of optimally spaced reviews produces a knowledge base that is both broad and durable.</p>

<h2>Buffett's Learning Method: Depth Over Breadth</h2>
<p>Buffett does not try to know everything. He focuses on a few areas where he has a competitive advantage and learns everything he can about those areas. He calls this his circle of competence. Within that circle, he reads deeply and continuously. Outside the circle, he does not invest. This principle applies to language learning as well. You do not need to learn every word in a language. You need to learn the words that matter for your goals. FluentCards starter decks focus on the most common and useful vocabulary for each language, building a foundation of high-frequency words that cover the majority of everyday communication.</p>
<p>Buffett's approach also emphasizes the importance of foundational knowledge. Before he could analyze a company, he had to understand accounting, finance, and economics. Before you can speak a language fluently, you need a foundation of core vocabulary and grammar. This foundation is built through repetition, review, and consistent practice. There are no shortcuts. Buffett read financial statements for years before he became a great investor. Language learners must review vocabulary for months before they become fluent. The process cannot be rushed, but it can be optimized.</p>

<h2>The Role of Technology in Accelerating Learning</h2>
<p>Buffett learned investing in an era without computers, without the internet, and without any of the information tools we take for granted. He manually read printed annual reports that he requested by mail. He manually calculated financial ratios on paper. He manually maintained his knowledge base throughindex cards and notebooks. Every piece of information required effort to acquire and organize. This made his dedication even more remarkable, but it also made the learning process slower and more laborious than it needs to be today.</p>
<p>Modern learners have advantages that Buffett did not have. Information is instantly accessible. Tools like FluentCards can organize knowledge and schedule reviews automatically. The FSRS algorithm optimizes the timing of each review based on your individual memory patterns, something that Buffett could only approximate through manual effort. TTS pronunciation provides accurate audio for any word in over twenty languages. AI mnemonics generate visual memory aids automatically. All of these tools reduce the friction of learning, allowing you to spend more time actually acquiring knowledge and less time managing the process.</p>

<h2>Applying Buffett's Principles to Language Learning</h2>
<p>Buffett's success teaches several lessons that apply directly to language learning. First, consistency matters more than intensity. Reading 500 pages every day is more effective than reading 3,500 pages once a week. Similarly, studying a language for thirty minutes daily produces better results than studying for three and a half hours on Sundays. The FSRS algorithm reinforces this principle by scheduling reviews at optimal intervals, but it cannot force you to show up. The streak tracker in FluentCards helps maintain consistency by providing a visible record of your daily practice.</p>
<p>Second, focus on compound knowledge. Every word you learn makes the next word easier to learn because your brain has more context to connect it to. The first thousand words in a language are the hardest and most important. After that, each new word adds to a growing network of associations that accelerates further learning. FluentCards starter decks focus on these high-frequency words, ensuring that you build the foundation that makes everything else easier.</p>
<p>Third, read material that interests you. Buffett does not read annual reports because he has to. He reads them because he genuinely wants to understand businesses and industries. Similarly, you should read content in your target language that you find genuinely interesting. If you love cooking, read recipes. If you love sports, follow sports news. If you love history, read historical articles. The more engaged you are with the content, the more effectively your brain will encode the language.</p>
<p>Fourth, trust the process and be patient. Buffett has been reading for over seventy years. He did not become the world's greatest investor overnight. Language learning follows the same trajectory. Progress is invisible in the short term but undeniable in the long term. Each review adds to your knowledge base, and that knowledge compounds over time. The FSRS algorithm ensures that each review is scheduled as efficiently as possible. Your job is to show up, do the work, and trust that the cumulative effect of thousands of small efforts will produce the result you want.</p>

